com/api/questions/22195/relationships/activeRevision"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"packs":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/packs","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/packs"}},"revisions":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/revisions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/revisions"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22195"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/content"}},"specialtyTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/specialtyTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/specialtyTags"}},"primaryTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/primaryTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/primaryTags"}},"contributionTypes":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/contributionTypes","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/contributionTypes"}},"contributors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/contributors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/contributors"}},"contribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/contribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/contribution"}},"myContribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/myContribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/myContribution"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96004"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/activeRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/activeRevision"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47871"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15152/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of recently diagnosed chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He reports mild breathlessness when walking up two flights of stairs but is otherwise managing his daily activities well. He has not experienced any exacerbations requiring hospitalisation or oral corticosteroids in the past year. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history but quit six months ago. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 78/min, blood pressure 132/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals mildly reduced air entry bilaterally with no wheeze. His modified Medical Research Council (mMRC) dyspnoea score is 1 and his COPD Assessment Test (CAT) score is 8.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpirometry performed three weeks ago shows FEV1 65% predicted with FEV1/FVC ratio 0.62.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial pharmacological therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long-acting beta-2 agonist plus inhaled corticosteroid","Short-acting beta-2 agonist as required","Inhaled corticosteroid","Long-acting muscarinic antagonist","Long-acting muscarinic antagonist plus long-acting beta-2 agonist"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild COPD based on his symptom profile and spirometry results. According to the Australian COPD-X guidelines, the approach to pharmacological management begins with assessment of symptom burden and exacerbation risk. This patient has low symptom burden (mMRC score 1, CAT score 8) and low exacerbation risk (no exacerbations in the past year), with moderate airflow limitation (FEV1 65% predicted).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort-acting beta-2 agonist as required\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial pharmacological therapy according to Australian COPD-X guidelines. For patients with mild symptoms and infrequent exacerbations, short-acting bronchodilators are recommended as first-line therapy. Short-acting beta-2 agonists (such as salbutamol) are preferred over short-acting muscarinic antagonists (such as ipratropium) due to concerns about increased cardiovascular adverse events and mortality associated with increased ipratropium use. These medications provide effective symptom relief when used as needed and are appropriate for patients who do not require regular maintenance therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if the patient had persistent symptoms despite optimal use of short-acting bronchodilators. The COPD-X guidelines recommend escalating to long-acting bronchodilators when short-acting therapy is insufficient for symptom control or when patients require frequent use of short-acting bronchodilators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting beta-2 agonist plus inhaled corticosteroid\u003C/strong\u003E combination therapy is reserved for patients with more severe symptoms, frequent exacerbations, or features of asthma-COPD overlap. This patient\u0027s mild symptoms and absence of exacerbations do not warrant combination therapy as initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled corticosteroid\u003C/strong\u003E monotherapy is not recommended for COPD at any stage. Inhaled corticosteroids are indicated only for patients with frequent exacerbations despite bronchodilator therapy and should always be used in combination with long-acting bronchodilators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist plus long-acting beta-2 agonist\u003C/strong\u003E dual bronchodilator therapy is reserved for patients with persistent symptoms despite monotherapy with a long-acting bronchodilator. This represents a significant escalation from initial therapy and is not appropriate as first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian approach emphasises a stepwise escalation of therapy based on symptom control and exacerbation frequency. Starting with short-acting bronchodilators allows for assessment of response before committing to regular long-acting therapy. If symptoms persist or worsen, treatment can be escalated according to the patient\u0027s needs. This patient should also continue non-pharmacological interventions including smoking cessation support, pulmonary rehabilitation if indicated, and annual influenza vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Short-acting beta-2 agonists are the preferred initial pharmacological therapy for mild COPD according to Australian guidelines.","COPD management is based on symptom burden and exacerbation history rather than spirometry severity alone.","Long-acting bronchodilators are reserved for patients with persistent symptoms despite short-acting bronchodilator therapy."],"references":["Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease. Global Strategy for the Diagnosis, Management, and Prevention of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease: 2025 Report. Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease; 2024. Available at: https://goldcopd.org/2025-gold-report/","Lung Foundation Australia. The COPD-X Plan: Australian and New Zealand Guidelines for the management of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease 2024. Version 2.77. Yang IA, George J, McDonald CF, Disler R, Ordman R, Goodwin A, Smith B, McNamara R, Zwar N, Dabscheck E, authors. Milton (QLD): Lung Foundation Australia; December 2024. Available from: https://copdx.org.au/copd-x-plan/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96004"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22195"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113989/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96004"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T17:25:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T17:30:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15152"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96004/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96004/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","